Why do you want to be in the Air Force?

Well sir, there are several reasons. Firstly,there is a long tradition of military service in my family. My dad was a hospital corpsman in the Navy, my grandfather work on KC-135s in the Air National Guard. My great-grandfather was in the infantry in the 2nd Marine Divison during WWII and took part in several beach landings in the Pacific. I've had two uncles in the Navy, another uncle was an Army Officer, and a step-brother in the Marine Corps who did a tour in Iraq. So, throughout my life the themes of military service and its benefits have been especially prevalent. Secondly, for specifically why I chose the Air Force, I've researched the Air Force and found it to be the most contemporary military branch. I believe this is true for its mission, the technology it uses, and its philosophy. Because of that, I believe the Air Force to be the most important and strongest force of change to global policy in the U.S. Military. Another reason why I chose the Air Force was because of its vast educational opportunities. I love learning and I would take full advantage of any continuing education opportunities presented to me. I also want to test and better myself. I also want to experience the comaraderie that military service creates because I think it's very healthy way to live giving and recieving some much support for one another. 
Comaraderie 
Patriotism, love the country


Describe when you were a leader?

There have been several instances where I was leader. Most frequently in my engineering classes during team design projects, I have often established myself as the Team Lead. For example, in Fall 2015 during my Software Engineering Class, our team was tasked to emulate the software development process in a term-long design project. I volunteered to lead the team which consisted of a couple of my friends and also a couple of people I didn't know very well. My responsibilities included organizing design and process meetings, dividing tasks among team members, measuring progress, helping any blocked teammates, communicating with the Professor, as well as my own development tasks. We were tasked to build a web application that KU students and staff would benefit from. We decided to build a website that would aggregate all of KU Social Media presence into one page or dashboard where a user could customize the content on said dashboard. There were some bumps along the way including miscommunication by the Professor with regards to deadlines and project requirements and at times teammates not motivated to complete their tasks. So, I fought poor communication with good communication and made my teammates more accountable by using google docs so I and the rest of team could see everybodys progress day to day on design documents, the project report, and actual code. Overall, I was very pleased with my teams performance which shows because we recieived an A on the whole project and subsequently an A in the class. Another opportunities I took to lead a team was during my Digital Systems Design course. There was a final design project where I again volunteered to lead the team which consisted of myself and two friends. Most recently, during my internship at Cerner, I demostrated leadership capabilities when I had the opportunity to help and mentor a fellow intern. I had arrived at Cerner a few weeks earlier than the other two interns that were assigned to my team. So I was already pretty well adapted by the time they arrived. One of the interns was going to be working on a very similar enviroment to what I was working so I felt obliged to help him through the same process I had gone through weeks prior. I soon found out that he had very little experience with object-oriented programming and web development so he required quite a bit of help. So whenever he needed help I would help him. When I couldn't help him, his manager could. 



